text: *  Luiz Alberto Beraldo Moraes  luizmoraes@ffclrp.usp Molecular Biology Reports  https://doi.org/10.1007/s11033-018-4411-5 Bioguided isolation, characterization and media optimization  for production of Lysolipins by actinomycete as antimicrobial  compound against Xanthomonas citri subsp. citri Júlia Pereira Rodrigues1 · Ana Paula Ferranti Peti1 · Fernanda Salés Figueiró1 · Izadora de Souza Rocha1 ·  Vinicius Ricardo Acquaro Junior1 · Tamires Garcia Silva2 · Itamar Soares de Melo3 · Franklin Behlau2 ·  Luiz Alberto Beraldo Moraes1  Received: 2 August 2018 / Accepted: 26 September 2018  © Springer Nature B.V. 2018

Abstract Citrus Canker disease is one of the most important disease in citrus production worldwide caused by gram-negative bacterial  pathogen Xanthomonas citri subsp. citri, leading to great economic losses. Currently, a spray of copper-based bactericides  is the primary measure for citrus canker management. However, these measures can lead to the contamination of soil by  metal contamination, but also the development of copper-resistant Xanthomonas populations. Considering the need to  discovery new alternatives to control the citrus canker disease, actinomycetes isolated from the Brazilian Caatinga biome  and their crude extracts were tested against different strains of Xanthomonas citri subsp. citri. Streptomyces sp. Caat 1-54  crude extract showed the highest antibiotic activity against Xcc. The crude extract dereplication was performed by LC–MS/ MS. Through bioassay-guided fractionation strategy, the antimicrobial activity was assigned to Lysolipins, showing a MIC  around 0.4–0.8 µg/mL. Growth media optimization using statistical experimental design increased the Lysolipins production  in three-fold production. The preventive and curative effects of the optimized crude extract obtained by experimental design  of Caat-1-54 against citrus canker were evaluated in potted ‘Pera’ sweet orange nursery trees. Caat 1-54 extract was effective  in preventing new infections by Xcc on leaves but was not able to reduce Xcc population in pre-established citrus canker  lesions. Streptomyces sp. Caat 1-54 extract is a promising, environmentally-friendly source of antimicrobial compound to  protect citrus trees against citrus canker. Collision-induced dissociation  Response surface methodology  Minimum inhibitory concentration  Dimethyl sulfoxide  Thiazolyl blue tetrazolium bromide  Thin-layer chromatography Citrus canker, caused by the gram-negative bacterial patho- gen Xanthomonas citri subsp. citri—Xcc (syn. X. citri, X.  campestris pv. citri, X. axonopodis pv. citri) [1], is one of  the major constraints to citrus production worldwide [2].  Damage to fruit is the most significant effect of the disease.  The lesions increase premature drop and reduce the market- ability of fresh fruit, not only by affecting the quality of the  peel, but also by interfering with the international fruit trade,  especially to canker-free citrus-producing areas, which can  lead to substantial economic impact [3]. For effective disease control, multiple applications are  needed. Spray of copper-based bactericides is currently the  primary measure for citrus canker management worldwide  [4]. As a consequence, the long-term use of copper bacteri- cides may not only affect the environment and the health of  the citrus trees due to the accumulation of metallic copper  in soils and ground water, but also favor the development  of copper-resistant Xanthomonas populations [5, 6]. The  emergence of copper resistant strains of Xcc has prompted  screening to discover new antimicrobial drug candidates  and subsequently develop agro-friendly compounds. Act- inobacteria have been recognized as a promising source of  bioactive compounds with potential for the development of  antibiotics. Streptomyces species are remarkable producers  of bioactive metabolites [7, 8]. However, the chemical diver- sity presented by actinomycetes warrants a closer analysis,  once a significant number of new compounds have been  discovered [9, 10]. Thus, especially unexplored ecosystems  represent promising sources of new antibiotics [11].

The Caatinga biome is a unique habitat, having under- gone little exploration. The Caatinga is a tropical dry forest,  located in a semi-arid region in Northeast Brazil. This biome  is strongly affected by anthropogenic processes and harbors  ecosystems that are home to microorganisms adapted to  extreme environmental conditions such as high temperature,  UV radiation, hydric stress, salinity, and nutrient deficiency  [12]. Pacchioni et al. demonstrated that the microbial pro- file of the Caatinga is remarkably different from those of  other Brazilian biomes such as the Amazon, savannah (also  called Cerrado), and the Atlantic forest [13]. Actinomycetes  from the Caatinga are known to often possess distinct physi- ological and biochemical properties and produce unique sec- ondary metabolites that are potentially active against other  microorganisms [13]. Microbial secondary metabolites display a diverse array  of chemical structures that can interact with various biologi- cal targets for specific purposes. In standardized laboratory  conditions, the production of these metabolites is restricted  to small or minuscule amounts [14, 15]. Cultivation condi- tions dramatically affect the production of secondary metab- olites. The determination of suitable carbon, nitrogen, and  mineral sources as well as factors such as pH and tempera- ture can directly impact the microbial growth rate and the  metabolite yield during fermentative processes [16, 17]. For  instance, the central composite design under the response  surface methodology (RSM) has been successfully employed  to improve fermentative conditions and elucidate the optimal  values of the most significant independent variables involved  in the Streptomyces fermentative process [18–20]. Hence,  this  work  aims  to  obtain  secondary  metabo- lites from actinobacteria isolated from Caatinga biome as  potential antibacterial compounds against Xcc. In this con- text, the most promising crude extract was dereplicated by  LC–MS/MS and the fermentative process was optimized by  experimental design, in order to improve the production of  Lysolipins (active metabolites). Subsequently, to prove the  applicability of crude extract, curative and preventive assays  was performed against citrus canker on sweet orange nursey  trees.

Potato dextrose (PD), Yeast malt broth (ISP 2), Glucose  yeast extract (GYE), Nutrient medium (NM) and Potato  dextrose agar (PDA) were acquired from Neogen culture  media (Lab M Limited, Lancs, UK). Tryptic soy broth (TSB)  was purchased from Oxoid (Oxoid Brasil Ltda, SP, BR).  Chemical (formic acid, Resazurin, NaCl and  MgSO4) and  the standard tetracycline were obtained from Sigma-Aldrich  (St. Louis, MO, USA). Solvents (acetonitrile, methanol and  ethanol) were HPLC grade purchased from JT Baker (Phil- lipsburg, USA). Aqueous solution were prepared by using  ultrapure water obtained from Milli-Q (18 MΩ cm) system  (Millipore, São Paulo, Brazil). 100 × 15 mm petri dishes and  filter paper of medium porosity were purchased from Fisher  Scientific (Pittsburg, PA, USA). Actinobacteria used in this study were provided by the Col- lection of Microorganisms for Agricultural and Environmen- tal Importance (CCMA, EMBRAPA, Brazil) and isolated  in the same methodology described by Silva et al. [21]. The  actinomycetes were maintained in glycerol (20%, v/v) as  mycelia fragments, and reactivated on plates containing a  potato dextrose agar media (PDA). All actinobacteria stud- ied were isolated from the Caatinga biome. Specifically, the  Caat 1-54 was isolated near highway BR 428, Petrolina, Per- nambuco state, Brazil (09°10′44.32″S and 40°22′36.67″W). In vitro antagonism bioassay

To test the ability of individual actinomycetes to inhibit the  growth of Xcc, antagonism bioassays were performed based  on studies conducted by Lingakumar et al. [22]. Actino- mycetes were streaked onto the center of PDA plates and  grown for 7 days at room temperature. The bacterial sus- pension (0.5 McFarland standard [23]) was then streaked  orthogonally to the actinomycetes. After 24 h, the plates  were examined for inhibition of bacterial colonies. The Xcc  strains used in all bioassays are listed in Table S1. To  evaluate  the  antimicrobial  activity  of  crude  extracts  against Xcc obtained by actinomycetes fermentation, bio- assays were performed using an agar disc method based on  the Bauer and Kirby protocol [24]. In this assay, each plate  contained five paper discs impregnated with 50 µg of crude  Molecular Biology Reports Molecular Biology Reports  extract prepared in methanol. Methanol was used as a nega- tive control, and tetracycline was used as a positive con- trol. The paper discs were placed on plates containing PDA  media, and after 24 h, a suspension of the target bacteria (0.5  McFarland standard) was dispersed on the surface of the  agar. Inhibition zones were assessed by thiazolyl blue tetra- zolium bromide (MTT) staining after 24 h of incubation. Bioassay‑guided fractionation

To analyze the Caat 1-54 crude extract, a liquid chromatog- raphy method was developed using a preparative LC-UV  system (Shimadzu) with a binary pump. The following con- ditions were used: gradient elution with methanol and water  with 0.1% formic acid; flow rate of 1 mL/min (analytical  mode) or 16 mL/min (preparative mode); detection at 280  and 310 nm; and a Shim-Pack C18 column (4.6 × 250 mm  in analytical mode or 19.0 × 250 mm in preparative mode). Fractionation of the crude extract was performed and  each fraction was bioassayed against Xcc strain 306. For  the bioassay, 2 mL of each fraction was dried and solubilized  in 10 µL of methanol. A 5 µL aliquot of each sample was  applied to a thin layer chromatography (TLC) plate, which  was not subjected to the chromatographic process. The TLC  plates were covered with PDA media and after 24 h a bacte- rial suspension (0.5 McFarland standard) was spread on top  of the medium. Inhibition zones were verified using MTT  staining after 24 h of incubation of the bacteria. HPLC–MS/MS analysis of Lysolipin and its analogs

The characterization of Lysolipins within the crude extracts  generated in this project was performed by liquid chroma- tography–tandem  mass  spectrometry  (LC–MS)  using  a  Waters Acquity UPLC™ system/Waters Xevo™ TQ-S mass  spectrometer equipped with an electrospray ion source. The  parameters used were:  N2 desolvation gas at 300 °C; scan  time 0.5 s with full scan from m/z 100 to 1400; source tem- perature 120 °C; capillary 3.2 kV and 60 V cone for ESI +,  and capillary − 3.2 kV and cone − 60 V for ESI in nega- tive mode. The chromatographic conditions were: Ascentis  Express HPLC Column F5 (10 cm × 2.1 mm, 2.7 µm), 10%  A (acetonitrile with 0.1% formic acid), and 90% B (ultrapure  water with 0.1% formic acid), ranging from 90 to 10% A up  to 12 min and returning to the initial condition to 15 min at  a flow rate of 0.5 mL/min. For collision-induced dissociation  (CID) experiments (15–50 eV), the most appropriate colli- sion energy was chosen for each selected ion. The data was  acquired using the MassLynx V4.1 software. HR-MS  analysis  was  processed  using  a  TripleTOF®   5600+ System from AB Sciex (Foster, CA, USA) equipped  with a Turbo V IonSpray and Calibrant Delivery System  (CDS), operated in positive mode. The optimized parameters

were as follows: gas: 1:60 psi; gas: 2:40 psi; curtain gas:  25 psi; ion spray voltage: 5 kV; turbo temperature: 550 °C;  range of m/z for product ion experiments: 50–650 in MS/ MS experiments and 200–1500 in full scan mode; and dwell  time: 100 ms Mass calibration (< 2 ppm) was performed  using  atmospheric-pressure  chemical  ionization  (APCI)  Positive Calibration Solution (AB Sciex, Foster, CA, USA).  A binary gradient of water (A) and acetonitrile (B) both  acidified with 0.1% formic acid was employed, starting at  10% of B, increasing to 80% in 6 min, maintained to 8 min,  increasing to 95% in 10 min and maintained for 12 min. NMR experiments were performed in a Bruker® Advance  DRX-500 spectrometer (Billerica, MA USA). All samples  were solubilized in deuterated methanol at 10 mg/mL and  analyzed by 1D and 2D (HMBC and HMQC) experiments.  1H and 13C NMR spectra were recorded in 500 MHz and  the identification was performed by spectral analysis and  comparison with literature data. Variation in fermentative conditions

Initially, the Caat 1-54 actinobacteria were fermented in five  different culture media: PD [25] (200 mL of potato broth and  20 g of dextrose), GYE [26] (10 g of yeast extract and 10 g  of dextrose), ISP-2 [27] (10 g malt extract, 4 g yeast extract  and 4 g dextrose), TSB [28] (17 g the enzymatic digestion  product of casein, 3 g the enzymatic digestion product of  soybean meal, 5 g NaCl, and 5 g dextrose), and NM [29]  (4 g meat extract and 5 g peptone). Later, the carbon source  of the ISP-2 media was changed from dextrose to xylose,  arabinose, dextrose, fructose, galactose, sucrose and malt- ose, respectively. In all experiments, the actinobacteria were cultivated  in 125 mL Erlenmeyer flasks containing 25 mL of growth  media, shaken at 150 rpm, a temperature of 30 °C, and mon- itored for a period of 12 days. The organic extracts were  obtained by solid phase extraction with C18 cartridges,  where 15 mL of sample was added, and then extracted with  5  mL  of  methanol,  obtaining  the  crude  extract  for  each  experiment. Screening of the main factors that influence  Lysolipins production by central composite design The central composite design  24 was applied to the following  independent variables: NaCl (mmol), sucrose (%), tempera- ture (ºC), and nitrogen source- malt extract and yeast extract  (%) in the ISP-2 media, in order to optimize Lysolipins  production (Table S2). The dependent variable evaluated  (response)  was  the  sum  of  the  total  area  of  Lysolipins.

Twenty-six experiments were performed: 16 at factorial  points (− 1, + 1), 8 in the axial points (− 2.00, + 2.00), and  2 in the central point (0, 0), completely randomized. The  data was analyzed with software Statistica 13.0 (TIBCO®  Statistica™, CA, USA). Minimum inhibitory concentration experiments The minimum inhibitory concentration (MIC) assays were  performed by microplate dilution (96 holes). The Xcc seed  culture was performed in TSB growth media. The turbidities  of Xcc suspensions were standardized at 0.5 on the McFar- land scale [23]. Dilutions were performed from columns 2  to 11 (D1–D10). Column 1 was the positive control, com- posed of growth media (TSB), bacterial suspension, and tet- racycline. The negative control, in column 12, consisted of  medium, bacterial suspension, and DMSO. After 24 h, the  microplate was developed by adding 0.02 mg/mL Resazurin  to each well of the microplates. The MIC concentration was  established as the lowest concentration of the compound in  which Xcc did not grow. Potential antimicrobial agent for control of citrus  canker

The preventive and curative effects of the crude  extract  of Streptomyces sp. Caat-1-54 against citrus canker were  evaluated in potted ‘Pera’ sweet orange nursery trees kept  under greenhouse conditions. In the preventive assays, the  crude extract was sprayed at 200 mg/L onto the upper and  lower sides of the leaves until run off using a hand sprayer  24 h before applying the Xcc inoculum. Plastic bags were  used as humidity chambers for 24 h before and after inocu- lation with Xcc. The bacterial suspension was prepared in  sterile distilled water buffered with 10 mmol of magnesium  sulfate  (MgSO4) using Xcc strain 306 [30] at  106 colony- forming units (cfu)/mL grown previously for 24 h on nutri- ent agar plates. The concentration of bacterial suspension  was adjusted to  108 cfu/mL with a spectrophotometer (O.D  600 nm = 0.3) and diluted 100 times before inoculation.  Trees which the leaves were sprayed with buffered water  or the solvent dimethyl sulfoxide (DMSO) were used as  negative controls. For each treatment, 40 susceptible leaves  at vegetative stage V5 [31] from four trees (ten leaves per  tree) were marked and monitored. The leaves were assessed  35 days after inoculation with Xcc strain 306 regarding  the number of citrus canker lesions/cm2. Foliar area was  calculated individually using the ImageJ software (version  1.51w). In the curative assays, 40-day-old citrus canker lesions  were covered with 10 µL/lesion of the same treatments used  in the preventive tests. The lesions were produced under  greenhouse conditions by spraying susceptible ‘Pera’ sweet

orange leaves with a suspension of Xcc strain 306 at  106 cfu/ mL and keeping the plants in a humidity chamber for 24 h.  After a week, the treated leaves were collected, disinfested  with a 1 min rinse in 70% ethanol, and washed with a 1 min  rinse in sterilized distilled water. Seven ~ 4 mm individual  lesions (repetitions) for each treatment were excised from  the leaves using a 1 cm cylinder. The tissue discs were mac- erated individually in 1 mL phosphate buffer (0.1 M; pH  7.0). For each lesion, 100 µL of the original suspension and  the 1/10 and 1/100 dilutions were plated onto nutrient agar.  Plates were incubated at 28 °C for 96 h before assessing  the number of cfu. Before data analysis, dilution-adjusted  bacterial counts were transformed to  log10 cfu/lesion. The  preventive and the curative experiments were performed  three times each. The variance analysis and Turkey test  (p = 5%) were used to evaluate treatments using R software  (ver. 3.2.4). Antagonism and disc diffusion assays The 120 actinomycete isolates available in the laboratory,  from the rhizosphere of the Caatinga biome were assayed  against 13 different strains of Xcc, and 62 isolates (52%)  showed  antagonistic  inhibition.  Of  the  62  isolates  that  displayed activity against different Xcc strains, 42 (68%)  showed also any inhibitory halo in disc diffusion assays.  Streptomyces sp. Caat 1-54 crude extract showed the most  promising  antimicrobial  action  in  antagonism  and  disc  diffusion assays (Fig. 1a, b); their metabolites drastically  inhibited the growth of Xcc on PDA media. Based on these  results,  the  dereplication  and  optimization  of  the  crude  extract produced by the Caat 1-54 fermentative process were  performed. Dereplication of Streptomyces sp. Caat 1‑54 crude  extract

Dereplication studies of the Caat 1-54 crude extract was  performed by LC–MS/MS. Lysolipin I and Lysolipin X, the  main compounds detected in the active crude extract gener- ated is represented in Fig. 2. The Lysolipins are important  antimicrobial polyketides isolated from Streptomyces viola- ceoniger Tü 96 and Streptomyces tendae Tü 4042 [32, 33].  Studies with Lysolipin I have suggested that the mode of  antibacterial action may be based on an interaction with the   C55-lipid carrier bactoprenol, which is involved in inhibit- ing cell wall biosynthesis, and therefore is active at very  low concentrations (MIC 0.001 µg/mL) against both gram- positive and gram-negative bacteria [33]. Lysolipins contain  a large number of oxidoreductases, and are among the most  Molecular Biology Reports Molecular Biology Reports  Fig. 1   Inhibition zone (left right dashed arrow) in: a Antagonism assay of Caat 1-54 against different strains of Xcc. b Optical images of disc  diffusion assays were performed with Caat 1-54 crude extract on Xcc strain 306 Fig. 2   Structural formula of a Lysolipin I and b Lysolipin X highly modified polycyclic xanthones known to date. This  type of polycyclic xanthone moiety is rarely found in natu- rally produced bacterial metabolites. Another unusual struc- tural aspect of Lysolipins is the presence of a cyclic amide  (ring F), which is seldomly found in aromatic polyketides  (Fig. 2) [34].

Based on this, the frag- mentation proposed for the ion of m/z 598 is represented  in Fig. 4. The CID experiment performed for the ion of m/z  564 revealed the same fragmentation pattern which is the  loss of  CH2O (30 Da) and  CH3NH2 (61 Da) (Fig. 3c). The  CID experiment carried out for ion of m/z 616 (Fig. 3d) dem- onstrated a neutral loss of  H2O (18 Da) as well as losses of  30 Da and 61 Da, as noted for the Lysolipin I fragmentation  easily transformed by a dehydration to Lysolipin X which  through low pH and light, producing the aromatic ring C  [35] (Fig. 2). Due the instability of the molecule, normally,  the crude extract presents a pool of Lysolipin I and Lysolipin  X.

Isolation and characterization of Lysolipins Scaled-up fermentation of Streptomyces sp. strain Caat 1-54  was carried out in ISP-2 media and 250 mg of crude extract  was fractionated by preparative HPLC. Each fraction was  bioassayed against Xcc strain 306 by diffusion disc assay  and analyzed by direct infusion-mass spectrometry (DI-MS)  to identify the chemical profile. Many fractions exhibited  ments and UV absorption profile of: b Lysolipin I, c Lysolipin I (-Cl),  d Lysolipin X, and e Lysolipin X (-Cl) notable antimicrobial activity; however, the most active  fractions were Fr32–Fr35. These fractions presented a same  peak profile by DI-MS, which was not observed in the other  fractions. The active fractions were grouped and submitted  to LC-HRMS analysis (Fig. 5). The LC–MS chromatogram  for the active fraction showed one major peak at 4.54 min,  which corresponds to the ionic species [M + H] + of m/z  598.1097 suggesting the molecular formula  C29H24NClO11  (error 2.3 ppm), which was assigned to Lysolipin I. The  presence of Lysolipin I (Fig. 2b) in grouped fractions was  confirmed by 1H, HMBC, and HMQC NMR experiments  Molecular Biology Reports Molecular Biology Reports  Fig. 4   Proposed fragmentation for ion m/z 598 (Lysolipin I)

The  analytical  technique  developed  herein  allowed for sensitive determination of the metabolic profiles. Effect of culture media on the production  of Lysolipins The production of Lysolipins by Streptomyces sp. strain Caat  1-54 was evaluated in five different culture media in order  to achieve the highest rate of production. The culture media  evaluated were PD, GYE, ISP-2, NM, and TSB. Accord- ing to the peak area chromatograms (Fig. S1), the ISP-2  media produced the highest level of Lysolipins, followed by  GYE and PD media. NM and TSB media did not produce  Lysolipins. The crude extracts obtained from different media were  also evaluated through the disc-diffusion bioassays against  the Xcc strain 306 (Fig. S2). The crude extract obtained  from ISP-2 media led to the biggest inhibition halo, which  was directly proportional to the peak area in chromatogram  of Lysolipins (Fig. S1). Therefore, ISP-2 media was selected  for further experiments. The constitution of growth media has been shown to  directly affect in the production of secondary metabolites  through the repression of biosynthetic enzymes [36]. Thus,  the choice of culture media is of fundamental importance  during antibiotic production by actinobacteria. Variation of carbon source The production of secondary metabolites can be limited due  to negative effects conferred by the carbon source. There are  several carbohydrates that are used as carbon sources for  growth, but also in secondary metabolite production; how- ever, some of them can be chosen for each function, sepa- rately. At the molecular level, the favored use of one carbon  source instead of another, and the production of secondary  metabolites reacts either to transcriptional activation [37]  or to repression [38, 39]. The repression by carbon source  is usually related to dextrose, maltose, sucrose, and xylose  interfering with the synthesis of secondary metabolites, via  repression of biosynthetic enzymes [40, 41].

In order to investigate the influence of different carbon  sources in Lysolipins production, the effect of xylose, ara- binose, fructose, galactose, sucrose and maltose in growth  media were evaluated. The ISP-2 was previously chosen  as reference growth media containing dextrose as carbon  source. The LC–MS chromatograms obtained for the crude  extracts generated for the Caat 1-54 fermentative process in  ISP-2 media containing different carbon sources is related  in Fig. S3. The Caat 1-54 fermentative processes conducted  in ISP-2 media containing sucrose, fructose, galactose, or  maltose produced Lysolipins. The crude extract of Caat 1-54  growth in ISP-2 media with sucrose resulted in the highest  Lysolipins peak area, so was chosen this carbohydrate as  the carbon source for further experiments (Fig. S3d). The  inhibition halo in bioassays (Fig. S4) was directly propor- tional to the chromatogram area of Lysolipins in the crude  extract (Fig. S3). Carbohydrates such as xylose and arabinose did not pro- vide efficient Lysolipins production, showing to be poor  carbon source for Caat 1-54. The Lysolipins production var- ied in different carbon sources and suggest that Lysolipins  production is affect by regulators which respond to carbon  source [42]. To increase the productivity, reduce the product cost as  well as the production cost, the variables that can affect the  growth media was optimized by a statistical experimen- tal design [43]. The variables such as NaCl concentration  (mmol), sucrose (%), temperature (ºC), and nitrogen source  (%) were selected in order to investigate significance varia- tion effect in the growth media.

In  total,  twenty-six  experiments  entirely  randomized  were performed: 16 at factorial points (− 1, + 1); 8 at the  axial points (− 2.00, + 2.00) and 2 at the central point (0,  0). From the experimental results, it was possible to obtain  an empirical mathematical model capable of predicting the  studied system (see Equation in Fig. 6) and response sur- faces (Fig. 6). According to the experimental design, 50 mmol of NaCl  provided the maximum production of Lysolipins (Fig. 6a, b,  d). Too low as well too high amounts of NaCl in the culture  media may influence the growth of the actinobacteria and  also the Lysolipins production, which is observed a sudden  drop in the production of the compounds under study. Zäh- ner et al. reported that a chlorine atom is present in the car- bon skeletons of Lysolipins [32] and the halogenase plays a  role in mediating chlorine insertion in these Lysolipins [44].  Thus, the NaCl concentration might be a possible chlorine  source to Lysolipin production. In addition, the NaCl added  in the culture media can increase the production of the sec- ondary metabolites in a certain concentration without impair  the growth of the producer actinobacteria [45]. Based on the experimental design, the optimum amount  of sucrose was obtained as 1.25% (Fig. 6a, c, e). The carbon  source is an essential component due to provide an energy  source and play an important role in the growth, primary,  and secondary metabolism. Furthermore, the carbon source  metabolized rate may affect the growth as well the produc- tion of secondary metabolites [43, 46]. The temperature (°C) demonstrated 31.3 °C as the opti- mum for the production of Lysolipins (Fig. 6b, c, f). Temper- ature has great influence on the growth of microorganisms  due to the fact that the growth process is linked to chemical  Molecular Biology Reports Molecular Biology Reports

Fig. 6   Optimum  response  surfaces  (Derringer  and  Suich)  for  Lysolipins I and X. a Sucrose (%)—NaCl (mmol/L); b Temperature  (°C)—NaCl (mmol/L); c Temperature (°C)—sucrose (%); d Nitrogen  reactions, which in turn are affected by temperature variation  [47]. The number of cell divisions per hour doubles with  each temperature increase of 10 °C [48]. This type of bacte- rial growth behavior is similar to enzyme-catalyzed chemical  reactions, thus demonstrating that growth is directly related  to a series of enzymatic reactions that have their optimal  temperature [47]. For nitrogen source the optimum production of Lysolipins  was obtained at 0.9% (Fig. 6d, e, f). The nitrogen source for  the actinobacteria was provided by malt and yeast extracts.  Similar to the carbon source, the nitrogen source was also  essential due to its active participation in both, primary and  secondary metabolism [46]. The mathematical model generated by the experimental  design presented a determination coefficient  (R2) of 0.717.  Therefore, it could explain 71.7% of the variations of the  data that occurred throughout the analysis process. In addi- tion, the lack of fit showed no significant effect (p > 0.05),  which indicates the model was well adjusted and can be used  to prediction (Table S4). It  can  be  considered  that  the  generated  model  could  achieve the optimal production conditions for the Lysolipins  (%)—NaCl  (mmol/L);  e  Nitrogen  (%)—sucrose  (%);  and  f  Nitrogen  (%)—Temperature  (°C)  and  the  empirical  mathematical  model—see  Equation such as: (0) 50 mmol NaCl, (0) 1.25% sucrose, (1) a tem- perature of 31.3 °C, and (− 1) 0.9% nitrogen source, which  can be seen in Fig. S5.

Afterwards, the optimum condition was performed and  compared to the predicted by the mathematical model. The  standard error obtained was < 5%, which confirms the good  agreement obtained by the generated model. Comparing the production of the sum of Lysolipins in  the ISP-2 standard culture media (area—799644.7) with  the optimum condition provided by the experimental design  (area—2884202.2), around three-fold increase was observed  (Fig. S6). Indeed, the experimental design proved to be effi- cient to optimize the fermentative conditions. It enabled  optimization of Lysolipins production through the investi- gation of the effect of the independent variables, and of the  interactions between them, to generate response surfaces and  a predictive mathematical model. It was found  that the MIC for Lysolipin I was around 0.8 µg/mL for Xcc- 10-4167 and FDC 1670 and around 0.4 µg/mL for Xcc strain  306, showing the potential of Lysolipins to be applied as  an antimicrobial agent against citrus canker (Fig. 7). The  minimum  inhibitory  concentrations  obtained  for  crude extract (Fig. S7) and the purified compounds were  similar, indicating that the antimicrobial active of crude  extract was related principally to Lysolipins in the extract.  Moreover, the facility to use the crude extract for treatment  instead of the purified Lysolipins. Consequently, the crude  extract can be directly applied for preventive treatment with- out any purification process, decreasing the time-consuming  and increasing the cost-effectiveness. Potential for control of citrus canker The extract of Caat 1-54 was effective in preventing cit- rus canker lesions when sprayed on sweet orange nursery  trees before the application of Xcc inoculum (Fig. 8 a, c–e).  The number of citrus canker lesions/cm2 on leaves of trees  treated with Caat 1-54 was significantly lower (80–93%)  than on trees sprayed with water or DMSO (Fig. 8c–e).  Nonetheless, the extract showed no curative activity, i.e. a  reduction of bacterial population, within the citrus canker  lesions (Fig. 8b, f–h). These results indicate that, similarly to  copper (4), the antimicrobial compound of Caat 1-54 extract  remains on the leaf surface after application acts as a barrier  against new infection events by Xcc. Moreover, the active  compound does not seem to act systemically in the plant or  penetrate through the leaf mesophyll upon application. It is evident from this study that actinomycetes are an excel- lent source of bioactive compounds, especially against Xcc.  The Caatinga environment is a rich habitat with highly valu- able bioprospects that need to be explored through increased  research and attention. The experimental design was able to  optimize the fermentation conditions in order to improve  the Lysolipins production. Caat 1-54 extract present a MIC  around 0.4–0.8 µg/mL and showed to be a promising, envi- ronmentally-friendly source of antimicrobial compound to  protect citrus trees against citrus canker. Additionally, fur- ther studies can be performed to investigate the optimal rate,  residual activity, and methods of application in the field. Molecular Biology Reports Molecular Biology Reports
